one sentence of description for a new feature is rarely enough.

What does this feature do?

We should probably look into getting that corrected to round to the appropriate value as Edm.Decimal (The redfish type for theses) does care about significant digits, even if in floating point they're essentially moot.

FWIW, these paths (and path segments) are now able to be documented in the YAML directly.

https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/blob/cc4ce70daa8ffed4848c15c5ddc50c51b31dda4a/yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/Metric/Value.interface.yaml#L99

@Ed
On Redfish side, there is no specification for different RW storage types (but just one) -

https://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/v1/ManagerDiagnosticData.v1_2_1.json
                "FreeStorageSpaceKiB": {
                    "description": "The available storage space on this manager in kibibytes (KiB).",
                    "longDescription": "This property shall contain the available storage space on this manager in kibibytes (KiB).",
                    "readonly": true,
                    "type": [
                        "integer",
                        "null"
                    ],
                    "units": "KiBy"
                },
                
Also, this further raises question that do we have any existing hardware in the OPEN community that supports 2 different types of RW storage? My understanding is that as per existing implementation that use-case doesn't exist in the OPEN community. Moreover, if we do need to support it then its better to have that as a completely new feature request and hence be handled separately as a different PR and implementation change.

My understanding was that ibm plaforms are currently using emmc?  As is gsj which uses estoraged.  I don't think gsj will care.

Lets ping those ibm platform maintainers and see if they care that this is only reporting spi flash on those platforms.

The only reason I bring this up is that as written, this is enabling this on all platforms unconditional.  So if the number is "wrong" on any platform, there's no out except to revert the patch.

AFAIK, IBM systems don't have _both_ a R/W SPI and a R/W eMMC though.  So, the presence or lack-there-of of this interface is just a matter of an implementation detail in phosphor-health-monitor and not part of the bmcweb commit.

The current phosphor-health-monitor config expects /run/initramfs/rw to be the RW volume.  The current eMMC implementation just blindly mounts over top `/var` which is broken anyhow but all they have to do is provide a phosphor-health-monitor config that uses /var instead of /run/initramfs/rw.

Either way, I don't see this as affecting the bmcweb commit.  The dbus path should still be the same on either implementation.

Lets double check that we agree on expectations.  In my opinion, this feature needs to be either:

A: Optionally selectable per platform (either through dbus or a meson option, strong preference for the former) so the platforms that have broken implementations don't give an incorrect answer to the user, and the user facing API remains correct.

B: Correct on all platforms.

Does that seems reasonable?  Or is there a third path I'm not considering?

C: The code leaves the unsupported statistic as nullptr in the JSON response.  (Perhaps this is a form of "A", as in missing dbus objects result in nullptr).  We do this all over bmcweb, don't we?  Missing objects result in no attribute being filled in.

@Jagpal, I think you need to exame all of the `if (ec)` paths in your `after*` calls.  I don't think any of them should be returning internalError, but instead should be setting `jsonValue[...] = nullptr`.

> C: The code leaves the unsupported statistic as nullptr in the JSON response. 

That's generally not how we've handled unsupported properties.  For unsupported, we omit them entirely.  null is used for "supported by this system, but not available right this moment".

> (Perhaps this is a form of "A", as in missing dbus objects result in nullptr).  We do this all over bmcweb, don't we?  Missing objects result in no attribute being filled in.

Yep, we do it all over, but generally we use the mapper to do it, where we look up a subtree of paths, and if they don't exist, we omit the properties entirely.  This patch took the approach of calling the daemon directly, which I think is fine in this case, but needs to handle "path isn't there" errors in a similar fashion to how we handle it in the mapper.  DBUS_USAGE.md documents all this intent.

> 
> @Jagpal, I think you need to exame all of the `if (ec)` paths in your `after*` calls.  I don't think any of them should be returning internalError, but instead should be setting `jsonValue[...] = nullptr`.

https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/b5f288d294e17719f30e32acc40e07681baf04b9/redfish-core/include/utils/collection.hpp#L35

And just return without populating anything.  Should be pretty doable to add and test.

> Yep, we do it all over, but generally we use the mapper to do it, where we look up a subtree of paths, and if they don't exist, we omit the properties entirely. This patch took the approach of calling the daemon directly, which I think is fine in this case, but needs to handle "path isn't there" errors in a similar fashion to how we handle it in the mapper.

We do call directly to the well known name in cases where we reasonably expect only one OpenBMC implementation to exist (systemd, mapper, etc).  Considering that this implementation is only for THIS manager, and THIS BMCs health metrics, it seems reasonable that only one implementation exists (sidenote, I actually prefer that, because it keeps people from inventing their own.) so I'm not going to enforce the mapper here, just that we handle the non-existence of the dbus name or path as a non-critical failure.

bmcweb shouldn't be enforcing a particular precision, as it doesn't have enough data about the underlying types to know the precision.  That needs to be done in the health daemon, similar to how it's done for sensors.

std::stod throws if the value isn't convertible to string, which is disallowed in url response handlers (because there's always a recovery that can be done locally.)

I suspect as part of removing the precision, this will go away.

https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/COMMON_ERRORS.md#5-using-methods-that-throw-or-not-handling-bad-inputs

Wait... what?  Isn't the requirement for reduced precision coming from some Redfish thing?  Why would you have decided to truncate the precision ever?

There is no reason that the dbus daemons should be doing rounding in order to make an external interface happy, right?

> Isn't the requirement for reduced precision coming from some Redfish thing?

Redfish uses EDM.Decimal to represent these kinds of things, which doesn't limit the precision in any kind of meaningful way.  In theory it's supposed to be producing fixed point values for any interface (ie 1.000), but considering almost no json library parses 1.000 differently than 1.0, the difference is moot in practice.

From a user perspective (as both a dbus user and Redfish user) there's an expectation is that sensors (and any dbus double interface) know their precision, and don't publish things that amount to floating point division rounding errors, as that would show up on a user facing API.

Temperature: 1.125
Is different to a human compared to
Temperature: 1.1250000000001

If things are producing the later, now bmcweb/the webui/any downstream client needs to make decisions about the value precision they want to display to users (as was done in this patch) that ideally would be handled upstream when the math is done, and we have more information about how many digits are available.


For this patchset, yes, bmcweb shouldn't be caring about precision.  It should be able to trust that the dbus daemon didn't produce floating point rounding issues.

I'm not sure that daemons should really be dealing with the fact that binary math and decimal math are different either, and we've certainly not documented or communicated this expectation anywhere.  I doubt outside of dbus-sensors any of the other daemons explicitly round to some precision level.

In the case of metrics, I'm not sure what you want to do.  We know there is 2GB of memory total and if 1.5234512 GB are used, that is a real number.  Saying the total percent is 76.17256 in the metric is a legitimate amount of precision that the daemon has, but you questioned it in the original commit message as being "too much precision".

The only obvious rounding I even see in dbus-sensors is an arbitrary 3 decimal places:

```
src/ADCSensor.cpp
38:static constexpr double roundFactor = 10000;     // 3 decimal places
173:            nvalue = std::round(nvalue * roundFactor) / roundFactor;
```

> I doubt outside of dbus-sensors any of the other daemons explicitly round to some precision level.

ADCSensor explicitly rounds, because of the division math it's doing.  3 Decimal points wasn't really documented, but was based on the fact that the N bit 0-3.3V ADCs in the AST2500 were N bits (N is 12 or 14, I don't remember), so system voltages aren't going to have "real" precision beyond 3 digits.  (The math might actually say 4 for most use cases, hence why I say "real").  With all the added scale stuff added to ADCSensor over the years, the math could probably be made more accurate, but it's not off by a lot for servers with rails in the  0-12V range.

My recollection is that other sensors functionally end up rounded because of how they do their math on the hwmon interfaces (at least they used to).  Maybe that changed over time.

> We know there is 2GB of memory total and if 1.5234512 GB are used, that is a real number.

Considering that the ManagerDiagnosticData/MemoryStatistics/TotalBytes definitions in schema are in integer bytes (Edm.Int64), not floating point (Edm.Decimal), the above is only an issue because this patch chose to implement the schema incorrectly.  Once it is appropriately setting them as integers (I'm assuming by flooring them to the closest int?), the problem you listed goes away.

It's unfortunate that dbus doesn't have a way to differentiate a floating point metric from a fixed point metric, but i'm not sure it's a huge issue.  static_cast<int64_t> isn't the end of the world, and should be right for most bmc use cases.

So as far as this patch goes can we agree that:

0. This patch needs tested against service validator, as is documented in the developing guide.  Testing.md lists service validator specifically.  Ideally it wouldn't have been marked ready to review until that had been done, but it is what it is.  As always, happy to help if you have pre-test patches that you need help with, it just saves time if you mark things WIP that haven't been tested yet.

1. This patchset needs to implement the Redfish schema properly for properties that are of type Edm.Int64.  I suspect this is going to mean calling static_cast<int64_t>(value) on the double for those specific properties.

2. Seeing metric values on a user facing API that have floating point rounding (like in the example on the original patch) are at best messy looking to a human, and at worst downright wrong to the OData spec.  They should be corrected.... SOMEWHERE so they don't show up in a user facing interface.

Seem reasonable?
